{meta: title Big Iron}
{meta: artist Marty Robbins}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]To the town of Agua Fria rode a stranger one fine [Am]day
[C]Hardly spoke to folks around him didn't have too much to [Am]say
[F]No one dared to ask his business no one dared to make a [C]slip
[Am]For the stranger there amongst them had a big iron on his hip
[F]Big iron on his [C]hip
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[Am]It was early in the morning when he rode into the town
[C]He came riding from the south side slowly looking all [Am]around
[F]He's an outlaw loose and running came the whisper from each [C]lip
[Am]And he's here to do some business with the big iron on his hip
[F]Big iron on his [C]hip
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
[Am]In this town there lived an outlaw by the name of Texas Red
[C]Many men had tried to take him and that many men were [Am]dead
[F]He was vicious and a killer though a youth of twenty [C]four
[Am]And the notches on his pistol numbered one an nineteen more
[F]One and nineteen [C]more
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[Am]Now the stranger started talking made it plain to folks around
[C]Was an Arizona ranger wouldn't be too long in [Am]town
[F]He came here to take an outlaw back alive or maybe [C]dead
[Am]And he said it didn't matter he was after Texas Red
[F]After Texas [C]Red
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
[Am]Wasn't long before the story was relayed to Texas Red
[C]But the outlaw didn't worry men that tried before were [Am]dead
[F]Twenty men had tried to take twenty men had made a [C]slip
[Am]Twenty one would be the ranger with the big iron on his hip
[F]Big iron on his [C]hip
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
[Am]The morning passed so quickly it was time for them to meet
[C]It was twenty past eleven when they walked out in the [Am]street
[F]Folks were watching from their windows everybody held their [C]breath
[Am]They knew this handsome ranger was about to meet his death
[F]About to meet his [C]death
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
[Am]There was forty feet between them when they stopped to make their play
[C]And the swiftness of the ranger is still talked about [Am]today
[F]Texas Red had not cleared leather when a bullet fairly [C]ripped
[Am]And the rangers aim was deadly with the big iron on his hip
[F]Big iron on his [C]hip
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 8}
[Am]It was over in a moment and the folks had gathered round
[C]There before them lay the body of the outlaw on the [Am]ground
[F]Oh he might have gone on living but he made one fatal [C]slip
[Am]When he tried to match the ranger with the big iron on his hip
[F]Big iron on his [C]hip
{end_of_verse}

